{"title_page": "Human trafficking in Mexico", "text_new": "'''Human trafficking''' is the [[trade]] of [[humans]], most commonly for the purpose of [[forced labour]], [[sexual slavery]], or [[commercial sexual exploitation]] for the trafficker or others. Mexico is a large source, transit, and destination country for victims of human trafficking.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Acharya|first=Arun Kumar|date=June 2016|title=Trafficking of Women and Children in Mexico: An Assessment of Anti-trafficking Laws.|url=http://web.a.ebscohost.com.ezproxy.rice.edu/ehost/pdfviewer/pdfviewer?vid=1&sid=f6523462-b3a8-4018-bbe4-ce6a18893516%40sessionmgr4010|journal=RCIS|volume=53|pages=5\u201321|via=EBSCO}} {{dead link|date=February 2018}}</ref>\n\nGovernment and NGO statistics indicate that the magnitude of forced labor surpasses that of forced prostitution in Mexico.<ref name=\"dos\" /> Groups considered most vulnerable to '''human trafficking in Mexico''' include women, children, indigenous persons, and undocumented migrants.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite journal | last1 = Servin | first1 = Argentina | last2 = Brouwer | first2 = Kimberly | last3 = Gordon | first3 = Leah | last4 = Rocha-Jimenez | first4 = Teresita | last5 = Staines | first5 = Hugo | year = 2015 | title = Vulnerability Factors and Pathways Leading to Underage Entry into Sex Work in Two Mexican-US Border Cities | url = | journal = Journal of Applied Research on Children: Informing Policy for Children at Risk | volume = 6 | issue = 1| pages = 1\u201317 }}</ref><ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":13\" /> Mexican women, girls, and boys are subjected to sexual servitude within the United States and Mexico, lured by false job offers from poor rural regions to urban, border, and tourist areas.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite journal|last=Curtis|first=James R.|last2=Arreola|first2=Daniel D.|date=July 1991|title=Zonas de Tolerancia on the Northern Mexico Border|jstor=215636|journal=Geographical Review|volume=81|issue=3|pages=333\u2013336}}</ref> Mexican trafficking victims were also subjected to conditions of forced labor in domestic servitude, street begging, and construction in both the United States and Mexico.<ref name=\"dos\">\"Mexico\". [https://www.state.gov/g/tip/rls/tiprpt/2010/142760.htm ''Trafficking in Persons Report 2010''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116203051/http://www.state.gov/g/tip/rls/tiprpt/2010/142760.htm |date=2012-01-16 }}. [[U.S. Department of State]] (June 14, 2010). {{PD-notice}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> U.S. State Department's [[Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons]] placed the country in [[Trafficking in Persons Report#Ranking System|\"Tier 2\"]]  in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/2017/271117.htm|title=Trafficking in Persons Report 2017: Tier Placements|website=www.state.gov|access-date=2017-12-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628043920/https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/2017/271117.htm|archive-date=2017-06-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Types ==\n{{See also|Human trafficking}}\nHuman trafficking in Mexico takes many forms, including sex trafficking and labor trafficking.<ref name=\":6\" /> Often, migrants being willingly smuggled are entrapped in one or more of these types of trafficking.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bernat|first=Frances P.|last2=Zhilina|first2=Tatyana|date=2010-04-12|title=Human Trafficking: The Local Becomes Global|journal=Women & Criminal Justice|volume=20|issue=1\u20132|pages=2\u20139|doi=10.1080/08974451003641289|issn=0897-4454}}</ref>\n\n=== Sex trafficking ===\n{{See also|Prostitution in Mexico|Gender inequality in Mexico}}\nWhile sex work is largely Illegal in Mexico, most cities do have [[Red-light district|Zonas de Tolerancia]], areas where prostitution is allowed. This has made Mexico a destination for sex tourism and one of the world's largest hubs for sex trafficking; It is the largest destination for sex tourism from the United States.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2005|title=Data and Research on Human Trafficking: A Global Survey|url=https://publications.iom.int/system/files/pdf/global_survey.pdf#page=100|journal=International Migration|volume=43|issue=1/2|pages=100\u2013145|via=|access-date=2017-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031121244/http://publications.iom.int/system/files/pdf/global_survey.pdf#page=100|archive-date=2017-10-31|url-status=live}}</ref> Sex work's profitability in Mexico has driven the forced exploitation of many girls as sex workers.<ref name=\":6\" /> Mexico is on the Tier 2 Watch List of the U.S. State Department's 2017 [[Trafficking in Persons Report]], a designation given to countries that do not meet the minimum standards of the Trafficking Victims Protection Reauthorization Act of 2003 (TVPRA), but which are still making efforts to comply with these guidelines, in large part because of its booming child sex trafficking industry; an estimated 16,000 to 20,000 Mexican and Central American children are thought to be victims of sex trafficking in the country<ref name=\":10\">{{cite journal | last1 = Cicero-Dominguez | first1 = Salvador | year = 2005 | title = Assessing the U.S.-Mexico Fight Against Human Trafficking and Smuggling: Unintended Results of U.S. Immigration Policy | url = | journal = Northwestern Journal of International Human Rights | volume = 4 | issue = 2| pages = 303\u201330 }}</ref> Mexico is rated as the second worst country in terms of child prostitution globally as of 2010.<ref name=\":11\">Monroy, P. (2010). Mexico: pasividad ante explotaci\u00f3n sexual infantil. Contralinea, Septiembre, Mexico DF, <nowiki>http://contralinea.info/archivo-revista/index.php/2010/</nowiki> 09/05/mexico-pasividad-ante-explotacion-sexual-infantil/</ref> Governmental ineffectiveness and rampant corruption have corroded trust in the Mexican government, which is evident in the declining rate of crime reporting in border regions of Mexico.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Bernat|first=Frances P.|last2=Winkeller|first2=Heather C.|date=2010-04-12|title=Human Sex Trafficking: The Global Becomes Local|journal=Women & Criminal Justice|volume=20|issue=1\u20132|pages=186\u2013192|doi=10.1080/08974451003641545|issn=0897-4454}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" />\n\n=== Labor trafficking ===\n{{See also|Human trafficking in the United States}}\nMexico is also host to large numbers of persons trafficked for labor purposes, though reliable statistics on their numbers do not exist.<ref name=\":10\" /> Victims are often migrants who engage smugglers voluntarily and are then forced into labor arrangements against their will.<ref name=\":0\" /> Additionally, many of these arrangements take place within the United States rather than within Mexico itself and are thus not necessarily included in Mexican trafficking statistics.<ref name=\":0\" /> Despite this, substantial amounts of trafficked labor, particularly in the form of domestic servitude, are known to be employed within Mexico itself.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n== Prevalence ==\nMexico is one of the global centers of the child prostitution trade and a source and transit country for large numbers of migrants moving northward from Central America.<ref name=\"dos\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":11\" /> There are an estimated 16,000 to 20,000 Mexican and Central American children who are trafficked for sex in Mexico.<ref name=\":10\" /> However, data on the number of victims of labor trafficking are not available.<ref name=\":0\" /> Additionally, the number of people trafficking into the United States from Mexico is known to vary widely, as do estimates of how many trafficking victims make such crossings.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe vast majority of foreign victims in forced labor and sexual servitude in Mexico are from [[Central America]], particularly [[Guatemala]], [[Honduras]], and [[El Salvador]]; many transit Mexico en route to the United States and, to a lesser extent, Canada and [[Western Europe]]. However, trafficking victims from South America, the Caribbean, Eastern Europe, Asia, and Africa are also found in Mexico, and some transit the country en route to the United States. Unaccompanied Central American minors, traveling through Mexico to meet family members in the United States, fall victim to human traffickers, particularly near the Guatemalan border. Mexican men and boys from Southern Mexico are found in conditions of forced labor in [[Northern Mexico]], and Central Americans, especially Guatemalans, are subjected to forced labor in southern Mexico, particularly in agriculture. Child sex tourism continues to grow in Mexico, especially in tourist areas such as [[Acapulco]] and [[Canc\u00fan]], and northern border cities like [[Tijuana]] and [[Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez]].\n\nBetween 2000 and 2002, approximately 135,000 children in Mexico were kidnapped, presumably for exploitation in prostitution, pornography, or illegal adoption trafficking.<ref name=\":5\" /> It is estimated that there are around 16,000 children engaged in prostitution in Mexico as of 2004.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==Structural causes==\n\n=== Poverty ===\n{{Main|Poverty in Mexico}}\n[[File:Mexican states by poverty rate 2010.png|thumb|401x401px|Mexican States by Poverty Rate]]\nMexico is characterized by persistent and extreme [[Economic inequality|income inequality]] and high rates of poverty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oecd.org/eco/surveys/Mexico-2017-OECD-economic-survey-overview.pdf|title=OECD Mexico Economics Survey|last=|first=|date=January 2017|website=OECD|publisher=OECD|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017201555/https://www.oecd.org/eco/surveys/Mexico-2017-OECD-economic-survey-overview.pdf|archive-date=October 17, 2017|access-date=October 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> These inequalities, and poverty in particular, can increase trafficking in several ways. Poverty often drives families to make decisions out of desperation and lack of education.<ref name=\"autogenerated22\">{{cite book|title=Trafficking in Humans: Social, Cultural and Political Dimensions|publisher=United Nations University Press|year=2008|isbn=978-92-808-1146-9|editor=Sally Cameron and Edward Newman|location=New York|pages=22\u201325|authorlink=Structural Factors in Human Trafficking}}</ref> For example, in the case of Mexico parents are especially likely to leave their families to go work in the United States and may become victims of traffickers.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nobles|first=Jenna|date=August 2013|title=Migration and Father Absence: Shifting Family Structure in Mexico|journal=Demography|volume=50|issue=4|pages=1303\u20131314|doi=10.1007/s13524-012-0187-8|issn=0070-3370|pmc=3766732|pmid=23355282}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.coha.org/modern-day-slavery-in-mexico-and-the-united-states/|title=Modern Day Slavery in Mexico and the United States|access-date=2017-11-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112131719/http://www.coha.org/modern-day-slavery-in-mexico-and-the-united-states/|archive-date=2017-11-12|url-status=live}}</ref> Furthermore, many victims of trafficking, especially in the case of sex trafficking, are not fluent in the language of their destination country and are limited in their ability to escape their situation.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite book|title=Sex Trafficking: Inside the Business of Modern Slavery|last=Kara|first=Siddharth|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2009|location=New York|pages=5\u201316}}</ref> In addition, victims often accept their positions because they feel that this is the only way that they may send some remittances to their family and their enslaved situations may in some cases still be better than their original impoverished and desperate state.<ref name=\"autogenerated22\" /> In this manner, poverty can both drive trafficking and prevent its victims from escaping it once they have been trafficked.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated22\" />\n\n=== Globalization ===\n{{See also|Globalization|}}\nThe rate of human trafficking has directly increased in correlation with [[globalization]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Sex Trafficking: Inside the Business of Modern Slavery|last=Kara|first=Siddharth|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0-231-13960-1|location=New York|page=17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Turner|first=Jackie|last2=Kelly|first2=Liz|date=November 2008|title=Trade Secrets: Intersections Between Diasporas and Crime Groups in the Constitution of the Human Trafficking Chain|jstor=23639517|journal=The British Journal of Criminology|volume=49| issue =  2|pages=184\u2013201|doi=10.1093/bjc/azn079}}</ref> Globalization has increased cross-border trade and the demand for cheap labor; however, migration policies of the U.S. and other countries have not changed with the level of demand for cheap labor, thus forcing people illegally to immigrate.<ref name=\"autogenerated22\"/> [[Illegal immigration to the United States|Illegal immigration]] then creates ideal conditions for organized criminal operations to form trafficking circles.<ref name=\"autogenerated22\"/> With increased trade of foreign goods to rural areas, import competition in the rural markets has also forced people in poor areas to migrate to industrialized economies for better livelihoods. Their desperate positions often make them subject to exploitation and trafficking into different forms of forced labor to support that economy.<ref name=\"autogenerated22\"/> Lastly, the technological advances that go hand in hand with globalization have facilitated the ease with which organized crime circles may conduct trafficking operations.<ref name=\"autogenerated22\"/>\n\n=== Sexual assault ===\nDuring the Central American civil wars throughout the 1980s, widespread sexual assaults of indigenous women were carried out, contributing greatly to the creation of the Mexican sex trafficking industry.<ref name=\":5\" /> Both policy and army personnel raped and assaulted several thousand poor, generally rural women during the [[Salvadoran Civil War|El Salvadorean]] and [[Nicaraguan Revolution|Nicaraguan]] civil wars.<ref name=\":5\" /> Many of these women were shamed by their communities and families and chose to migrate to Mexico, leading to a boom in sex trafficking.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Crawford|first=Mary|date=October 2016|title=International Sex Trafficking|journal=Women and Therapy|volume=40|pages=101\u2013122|doi=10.1080/02703149.2016.1206784}}</ref> As of 2014, this pattern of marginalization through sexual assault was still widespread.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Acharya|first=Arun Kumar|date=2014-03-04|title=Sexual Exploitation and Trafficking of Women and Girls in Mexico: An Analysis on Impact of Violence on Health Status|journal=Journal of Intercultural Studies|volume=35|issue=2|pages=182\u2013195|doi=10.1080/07256868.2014.885414|issn=0725-6868}}</ref>\n\nThe effect of conflict and ensuing assault on the development of the sex trade is domestic to Mexico as well as foreign. Internal conflict between organized crime and police forces and the military have historically lead to unusually high levels of instability in some areas of Mexico, most notably in the case of the [[Chiapas conflict|Chiapas Conflict]].<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite journal|last=Acharya|first=Arun Kumar|date=April 2004|title=Agrarian Conflict, Internal Displacement, and Trafficking of Mexican Women: The Case of Chiapas State|url=http://paa2004.princeton.edu/papers/40481|journal=Population Association of America|volume=|pages=|via=PAA}}</ref> Similarly to the Central American civil wars, the sexual violence that accompanied this conflict drove many shunned women to turn to sex work and helped jump start the sex trade in those regions of Mexico.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n==Anti-trafficking laws and policies==\nMexico ratified the [[United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime|United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime]] (or Palermo Convention) on April 11, 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://treaties.un.org/Pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=IND&mtdsg_no=XVIII-12&chapter=18&clang=_en|title=United Nations Treaty Collection|website=treaties.un.org|language=EN|access-date=2019-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306044115/https://treaties.un.org/Pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=IND&mtdsg_no=XVIII-12&chapter=18&clang=_en|archive-date=2019-03-06|url-status=live}}</ref> The Convention includes a [[Protocol against the Smuggling of Migrants by Land, Sea and Air|\"Protocol Against the Smuggling of Migrants by Land, Sea, and Air]]\" and a \"[[Protocol to Prevent, Suppress and Punish Trafficking in Persons, especially Women and Children|Protocol to Suppress, Prevent, and Punish Trafficking in Persons, Especially Women and Children]]\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cicero-Dominguez|first=Salvador A.|date=Winter 2005|title=Assessing the U.S.-Mexico Fight Against Trafficking and Smuggling: Unintended Results of U.S. Immigration Policy|url=http://scholarlycommons.law.northwestern.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1036&context=njihr|journal=Northwestern Journal of International Human Rights|volume=4|pages=|via=Scholarly Commons|access-date=2017-10-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171009093031/http://scholarlycommons.law.northwestern.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1036&context=njihr|archive-date=2017-10-09|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Congress of the Union|Congress of Mexico]] passed a law on human trafficking in 2007 after which the Federal District and all of the states passed anti-trafficking measures themselves.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Rietig|first=Victoria|date=November 2012|title=New Law, Old Impunity: Mexico has a new Anti-trafficking law, but will it Address the Country's Problems?|url=http://oxmofm.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/Rietig-FINAL.pdf|journal=Oxford Monitor of Forced Migration|volume=2|pages=|via=Oxford Monitor of Forced Migration|access-date=2017-10-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228013846/http://oxmofm.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/Rietig-FINAL.pdf|archive-date=2013-02-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> In an attempt to harmonize the varied penal codes on the subject of human trafficking, the government passed a new anti-trafficking law in 2012 that criminalized all participants in the act of trafficking (including consumers) and unified local laws.<ref name=\":3\" /> The law was further reformed in 2014.<ref name=\":4\" /> In an effort to address the demand for forced labor, the [[Secretariat of Labor and Social Welfare|Secretary of Labor and Social Welfare]] developed a series of workshops and trainings in 2010 to prevent child labor and trafficking for forced labor.<ref name=\"dos\" /> It included media materials that explain how labor recruiting agents can deceive individuals in order to recruit them for forced labor.<ref name=\"dos\" /> However, while Mexican officials recognize human trafficking as a serious problem, NGOs and government representatives report that some local officials tolerate and are sometimes complicit in trafficking, impeding implementation of anti-trafficking statutes.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\"dos\" /> Mexico has publicly endorsed the United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime\u2019s Blue Heart Campaign against Human Trafficking, becoming the first country in Latin America to do so.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/blueheart/en/about.html|title=About the Blue Heart|last=nancy.cao|website=www.unodc.org|access-date=2017-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803041919/http://www.unodc.org/blueheart/en/about.html|archive-date=2017-08-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Trafficking across the border with the United States==\n{{See also|Human trafficking in the United States|Human trafficking in Texas|Human trafficking in California|Human trafficking in Arizona|Coyotaje}}\n[[File:Border Region.png|thumb|330x330px|The U.S.-Mexico border with the area up to 100 miles from the border demarcated.]]\nA third of the people annually trafficked into the United States are from [[Latin America]], and the vast majority of these people enter the US through the [[Mexico-United States border]].<ref name=\":5\" /> This extremely porous border has historically been the site of one of the most protracted labor migrations in the world, and is North America's largest transit site for young children exploited in labor and sex trafficking as of 2011.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal | last1 = Butler | first1 = Cheryl | year = 2012 | title = Sex Slavery in the Lone Star State: Does the Texas Human Trafficking Legislation of 2011 Protect Minors? | url = | journal = Akron Law Review | volume = 45 | issue = | pages = 843\u201385 }}</ref> Texas is a particularly important transit site for domestic trafficking; around twenty percent of domestic trafficking victims pass through the state at some point on their journeys.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite journal | last1 = Ugarte | first1 = Marisa B.| last2 = Zarate | first2 = Laura | last3 = Farley | first3 = Melissa | author-link3 = Melissa Farley | title = Prostitution and trafficking of women and children from Mexico to the United States | journal = [[Journal of Aggression, Maltreatment & Trauma|Journal of Trauma Practice]] | volume = 2 | issue = 3/4 | pages = 147\u2013165 | doi = 10.1300/J189v02n03_08 | date = January 2004 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal | last1 = Garza | first1 = Rocio | year = 2011 | title = Addressing Human Trafficking Along the United States-Mexico Border: The Need for a Bilateral Partnership | url = | journal = Cardozo Journal of International and Comparative Law | volume = 19 | issue = 413| pages = 413\u201352 }}</ref>\n\n\"[[Coyotaje|Coyote]]\" is the colloquial term used to refer to migrant smugglers along the Mexico- United States border.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite journal | last1 = Hofmann | first1 = Susanne | year = 2015 | title = Borderline Slavery: Mexico, United States, and the Human Trade - Edited by Tiano, Susan and Murphy-Aguilar, Moira | url = | journal = Bulletin of Latin American Research | volume = 34 | issue = 2| pages = 279\u201381 | doi = 10.1111/blar.12321 }}</ref> In the past, the coyote-migrant relationship ended once the smuggler delivered the migrant to the U.S.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal | last1 = Chacon | first1 = Jennifer | year = 2006 | title = Misery and Mypoia: Understanding the Failures of U.S. Efforts to Stop Human Trafficking | url = | journal = Fordham Law Review | volume = 74 | issue = 6| pages = 2977\u20133040 }}</ref> However, it has become increasingly commonplace for coyotes to coerce migrants into exploitative labor arrangements upon reaching their destination in the U.S (frequently a different one from that which they paid to be smuggled to).<ref name=\":0\" /> These labor agreements frequently involve forced agricultural labor and/or sex work, conditions that migrants would never have consented to had they been previously aware of them.<ref name=\":0\" /> Coyotes use unpaid debt as a threat in order to force migrants into such arrangements. The rising costs of smuggling, a result of increased border security and enforcement, has made it far more common for migrants to become heavily indebted to smugglers.<ref name=\":0\" /> Additionally, the expansion of the coyote's role to include transporting migrants to a final destination within the U.S., rather than simply transporting them across the border, incurs additional expenses that the migrant must pay, and so increases the likelihood of their being exploited and trafficked by the coyotes as forced laborers or sex workers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSmugglers sometimes pretend to offer reduced fees to women and child migrants and then sexually assault or rape them as a form of substitute \"payment\".<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Estes|first=Richard J.|last2=Weiner|first2=Niel Alan|date=February 20, 2002|title=The Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children in the U.S., Canada, and Mexico|url=http://www.gems-girls.org/Estes%20Wiener%202001.pdf|journal=School of Social Work|volume=|pages=|via=|access-date=November 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229014824/http://www.gems-girls.org/Estes%20Wiener%202001.pdf|archive-date=December 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Human traffickers masquerading as coyotes often use false promises of guaranteed jobs to lure migrants, and will sometimes kidnap women and children along the journey, either for ransom from their families, or to be sold in the US into servitude or prostitution.<ref name=\":5\" /> Many unaccompanied children also make the crossing from Mexico to the U.S.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.unicefusa.org/mission/emergencies/child-refugees/central-america-child-migrants|title=Central America Child Migrants|work=UNICEF USA|access-date=2017-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922052810/https://www.unicefusa.org/mission/emergencies/child-refugees/central-america-child-migrants|archive-date=2017-09-22|url-status=live}}</ref> Unaccompanied minors are sometimes sold into prostitution by the trafficker, and their families are falsely led to believe that they died during transit.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nWithin the United States, the [[Victims of Trafficking and Violence Protection Act of 2000]] serves as a legal framework within which many perpetrators of trafficking are tried, but victims of trafficking are generally punished on equal footing with perpetrators if intercepted during the process of entering the country.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite journal|last=Kappelhoff|first=Michael J.|date=Fall 2008|title=Federal Prosecution of Human Trafficking Cases: Striking a Blow Against Modern Day Slavery|url=https://ir.stthomas.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://www.google.com/&httpsredir=1&article=1173&context=ustlj|journal=University of St. Thomas Law Journal|volume=6|pages=9\u201320|via=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Human rights in Mexico]]\n* [[International child abduction in Mexico]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Americas topic|Human trafficking in}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Human Trafficking In Mexico}}\n[[Category:Human trafficking in Mexico| ]]\n[[Category:Human trafficking by country|Mexico]]\n[[Category:Human trafficking in North America|Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "'''Human trafficking''' is the [[trade]] of [[humans]], most commonly for the purpose of [[forced labour]], [[sexual slavery]], or [[commercial sexual exploitation]] for the trafficker or others. Mexico is a large source, transit, and destination country for victims of human trafficking.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Acharya|first=Arun Kumar|date=June 2016|title=Trafficking of Women and Children in Mexico: An Assessment of Anti-trafficking Laws.|url=http://web.a.ebscohost.com.ezproxy.rice.edu/ehost/pdfviewer/pdfviewer?vid=1&sid=f6523462-b3a8-4018-bbe4-ce6a18893516%40sessionmgr4010|journal=RCIS|volume=53|pages=5\u201321|via=EBSCO}} {{dead link|date=February 2018}}</ref>\n\nGovernment and NGO statistics indicate that the magnitude of forced labor surpasses that of forced prostitution in Mexico.<ref name=\"dos\" /> Groups considered most vulnerable to '''human trafficking in Mexico''' include women, children, indigenous persons, and undocumented migrants.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite journal | last1 = Servin | first1 = Argentina | last2 = Brouwer | first2 = Kimberly | last3 = Gordon | first3 = Leah | last4 = Rocha-Jimenez | first4 = Teresita | last5 = Staines | first5 = Hugo | year = 2015 | title = Vulnerability Factors and Pathways Leading to Underage Entry into Sex Work in Two Mexican-US Border Cities | url = | journal = Journal of Applied Research on Children: Informing Policy for Children at Risk | volume = 6 | issue = 1| pages = 1\u201317 }}</ref><ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":13\" /> Mexican women, girls, and boys are subjected to sexual servitude within the United States and Mexico, lured by false job offers from poor rural regions to urban, border, and tourist areas.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite journal|last=Curtis|first=James R.|last2=Arreola|first2=Daniel D.|date=July 1991|title=Zonas de Tolerancia on the Northern Mexico Border|jstor=215636|journal=Geographical Review|volume=81|issue=3|pages=333\u2013336}}</ref> Mexican trafficking victims were also subjected to conditions of forced labor in domestic servitude, street begging, and construction in both the United States and Mexico.<ref name=\"dos\">\"Mexico\". [https://www.state.gov/g/tip/rls/tiprpt/2010/142760.htm ''Trafficking in Persons Report 2010''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116203051/http://www.state.gov/g/tip/rls/tiprpt/2010/142760.htm |date=2012-01-16 }}. [[U.S. Department of State]] (June 14, 2010). {{PD-notice}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> U.S. State Department's [[Office to Monitor and Combat Trafficking in Persons]] placed the country in [[Trafficking in Persons Report#Ranking System|\"Tier 2\"]]  in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/2017/271117.htm|title=Trafficking in Persons Report 2017: Tier Placements|website=www.state.gov|access-date=2017-12-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628043920/https://www.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/2017/271117.htm|archive-date=2017-06-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Types ==\n{{See also|Human trafficking}}\nHuman trafficking in Mexico takes many forms, including sex trafficking and labor trafficking.<ref name=\":6\" /> Often, migrants being willingly smuggled are entrapped in one or more of these types of trafficking.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bernat|first=Frances P.|last2=Zhilina|first2=Tatyana|date=2010-04-12|title=Human Trafficking: The Local Becomes Global|journal=Women & Criminal Justice|volume=20|issue=1\u20132|pages=2\u20139|doi=10.1080/08974451003641289|issn=0897-4454}}</ref>\n\n=== Sex trafficking ===\n{{See also|Prostitution in Mexico|Gender inequality in Mexico}}\nWhile sex work is largely Illegal in Mexico, most cities do have [[Red-light district|Zonas de Tolerancia]], areas where prostitution is allowed. This has made Mexico a destination for sex tourism and one of the world's largest hubs for sex trafficking; It is the largest destination for sex tourism from the United States.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2005|title=Data and Research on Human Trafficking: A Global Survey|url=https://publications.iom.int/system/files/pdf/global_survey.pdf#page=100|journal=International Migration|volume=43|issue=1/2|pages=100\u2013145|via=|access-date=2017-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031121244/http://publications.iom.int/system/files/pdf/global_survey.pdf#page=100|archive-date=2017-10-31|url-status=live}}</ref> Sex work's profitability in Mexico has driven the forced exploitation of many girls as sex workers.<ref name=\":6\" /> Mexico is on the Tier 2 Watch List of the U.S. State Department's 2017 [[Trafficking in Persons Report]], a designation given to countries that do not meet the minimum standards of the Trafficking Victims Protection Reauthorization Act of 2003 (TVPRA), but which are still making efforts to comply with these guidelines, in large part because of its booming child sex trafficking industry; an estimated 16,000 to 20,000 Mexican and Central American children are thought to be victims of sex trafficking in the country<ref name=\":10\">{{cite journal | last1 = Cicero-Dominguez | first1 = Salvador | year = 2005 | title = Assessing the U.S.-Mexico Fight Against Human Trafficking and Smuggling: Unintended Results of U.S. Immigration Policy | url = | journal = Northwestern Journal of International Human Rights | volume = 4 | issue = 2| pages = 303\u201330 }}</ref> Mexico is rated as the second worst country in terms of child prostitution globally as of 2010.<ref name=\":11\">Monroy, P. (2010). Mexico: pasividad ante explotaci\u00f3n sexual infantil. Contralinea, Septiembre, Mexico DF, <nowiki>http://contralinea.info/archivo-revista/index.php/2010/</nowiki> 09/05/mexico-pasividad-ante-explotacion-sexual-infantil/</ref> Governmental ineffectiveness and rampant corruption have corroded trust in the Mexican government, which is evident in the declining rate of crime reporting in border regions of Mexico.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Bernat|first=Frances P.|last2=Winkeller|first2=Heather C.|date=2010-04-12|title=Human Sex Trafficking: The Global Becomes Local|journal=Women & Criminal Justice|volume=20|issue=1\u20132|pages=186\u2013192|doi=10.1080/08974451003641545|issn=0897-4454}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" />\n\n=== Labor trafficking ===\n{{See also|Human trafficking in the United States}}\nMexico is also host to large numbers of persons trafficked for labor purposes, though reliable statistics on their numbers do not exist.<ref name=\":10\" /> Victims are often migrants who engage smugglers voluntarily and are then forced into labor arrangements against their will.<ref name=\":0\" /> Additionally, many of these arrangements take place within the United States rather than within Mexico itself and are thus not necessarily included in Mexican trafficking statistics.<ref name=\":0\" /> Despite this, substantial amounts of trafficked labor, particularly in the form of domestic servitude, are known to be employed within Mexico itself.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\n== Prevalence ==\nMexico is one of the global centers of the child prostitution trade and a source and transit country for large numbers of migrants moving northward from Central America.<ref name=\"dos\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":11\" /> There are an estimated 16,000 to 20,000 Mexican and Central American children who are trafficked for sex in Mexico.<ref name=\":10\" /> However, data on the number of victims of labor trafficking are not available.<ref name=\":0\" /> Additionally, the number of people trafficking into the United States from Mexico is known to vary widely, as do estimates of how many trafficking victims make such crossings.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe vast majority of foreign victims in forced labor and sexual servitude in Mexico are from [[Central America]], particularly [[Guatemala]], [[Honduras]], and [[El Salvador]]; many transit Mexico en route to the United States and, to a lesser extent, Canada and [[Western Europe]]. However, trafficking victims from South America, the Caribbean, Eastern Europe, Asia, and Africa are also found in Mexico, and some transit the country en route to the United States. Unaccompanied Central American minors, traveling through Mexico to meet family members in the United States, fall victim to human traffickers, particularly near the Guatemalan border. Mexican men and boys from Southern Mexico are found in conditions of forced labor in [[Northern Mexico]], and Central Americans, especially Guatemalans, are subjected to forced labor in southern Mexico, particularly in agriculture. Child sex tourism continues to grow in Mexico, especially in tourist areas such as [[Acapulco]] and [[Canc\u00fan]], and northern border cities like [[Tijuana]] and [[Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez]].\n\nBetween 2000 and 2002, approximately 135,000 children in Mexico were kidnapped, presumably for exploitation in prostitution, pornography, or illegal adoption trafficking.<ref name=\":5\" /> It is estimated that there are around 16,000 children engaged in prostitution in Mexico as of 2004.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==Structural causes==\n\n=== Poverty ===\n{{Main|Poverty in Mexico}}\n[[File:Mexican states by poverty rate 2010.png|thumb|401x401px|Mexican States by Poverty Rate]]\nMexico is characterized by persistent and extreme [[Economic inequality|income inequality]] and high rates of poverty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oecd.org/eco/surveys/Mexico-2017-OECD-economic-survey-overview.pdf|title=OECD Mexico Economics Survey|last=|first=|date=January 2017|website=OECD|publisher=OECD|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171017201555/https://www.oecd.org/eco/surveys/Mexico-2017-OECD-economic-survey-overview.pdf|archive-date=October 17, 2017|access-date=October 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> These inequalities, and poverty in particular, can increase trafficking in several ways. Poverty often drives families to make decisions out of desperation and lack of education.<ref name=\"autogenerated22\">{{cite book|title=Trafficking in Humans: Social, Cultural and Political Dimensions|publisher=United Nations University Press|year=2008|isbn=978-92-808-1146-9|editor=Sally Cameron and Edward Newman|location=New York|pages=22\u201325|authorlink=Structural Factors in Human Trafficking}}</ref> For example, in the case of Mexico parents are especially likely to leave their families to go work in the United States and may become victims of traffickers.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nobles|first=Jenna|date=August 2013|title=Migration and Father Absence: Shifting Family Structure in Mexico|journal=Demography|volume=50|issue=4|pages=1303\u20131314|doi=10.1007/s13524-012-0187-8|issn=0070-3370|pmc=3766732|pmid=23355282}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.coha.org/modern-day-slavery-in-mexico-and-the-united-states/|title=Modern Day Slavery in Mexico and the United States|access-date=2017-11-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171112131719/http://www.coha.org/modern-day-slavery-in-mexico-and-the-united-states/|archive-date=2017-11-12|url-status=live}}</ref> Furthermore, many victims of trafficking, especially in the case of sex trafficking, are not fluent in the language of their destination country and are limited in their ability to escape their situation.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite book|title=Sex Trafficking: Inside the Business of Modern Slavery|last=Kara|first=Siddharth|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2009|location=New York|pages=5\u201316}}</ref> In addition, victims often accept their positions because they feel that this is the only way that they may send some remittances to their family and their enslaved situations may in some cases still be better than their original impoverished and desperate state.<ref name=\"autogenerated22\" /> In this manner, poverty can both drive trafficking and prevent its victims from escaping it once they have been trafficked.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\"autogenerated22\" />\n\n=== Globalization ===\n{{See also|Globalization|}}\nThe rate of human trafficking has directly increased in correlation with [[globalization]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Sex Trafficking: Inside the Business of Modern Slavery|last=Kara|first=Siddharth|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0-231-13960-1|location=New York|page=17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Turner|first=Jackie|last2=Kelly|first2=Liz|date=November 2008|title=Trade Secrets: Intersections Between Diasporas and Crime Groups in the Constitution of the Human Trafficking Chain|jstor=23639517|journal=The British Journal of Criminology|volume=49| issue =  2|pages=184\u2013201|doi=10.1093/bjc/azn079}}</ref> Globalization has increased cross-border trade and the demand for cheap labor; however, migration policies of the U.S. and other countries have not changed with the level of demand for cheap labor, thus forcing people illegally to immigrate.<ref name=\"autogenerated22\"/> [[Illegal immigration to the United States|Illegal immigration]] then creates ideal conditions for organized criminal operations to form trafficking circles.<ref name=\"autogenerated22\"/> With increased trade of foreign goods to rural areas, import competition in the rural markets has also forced people in poor areas to migrate to industrialized economies for better livelihoods. Their desperate positions often make them subject to exploitation and trafficking into different forms of forced labor to support that economy.<ref name=\"autogenerated22\"/> Lastly, the technological advances that go hand in hand with globalization have facilitated the ease with which organized crime circles may conduct trafficking operations.<ref name=\"autogenerated22\"/>\n\n=== Sexual assault ===\nDuring the Central American civil wars throughout the 1980s, widespread sexual assaults of indigenous women were carried out, contributing greatly to the creation of the Mexican sex trafficking industry.<ref name=\":5\" /> Both policy and army personnel raped and assaulted several thousand poor, generally rural women during the [[Salvadoran Civil War|El Salvadorean]] and [[Nicaraguan Revolution|Nicaraguan]] civil wars.<ref name=\":5\" /> Many of these women were shamed by their communities and families and chose to migrate to Mexico, leading to a boom in sex trafficking.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Crawford|first=Mary|date=October 2016|title=International Sex Trafficking|journal=Women and Therapy|volume=40|pages=101\u2013122|doi=10.1080/02703149.2016.1206784}}</ref> As of 2014, this pattern of marginalization through sexual assault was still widespread.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Acharya|first=Arun Kumar|date=2014-03-04|title=Sexual Exploitation and Trafficking of Women and Girls in Mexico: An Analysis on Impact of Violence on Health Status|journal=Journal of Intercultural Studies|volume=35|issue=2|pages=182\u2013195|doi=10.1080/07256868.2014.885414|issn=0725-6868}}</ref>\n\nThe effect of conflict and ensuing assault on the development of the sex trade is domestic to Mexico as well as foreign. Internal conflict between organized crime and police forces and the military have historically lead to unusually high levels of instability in some areas of Mexico, most notably in the case of the [[Chiapas conflict|Chiapas Conflict]].<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite journal|last=Acharya|first=Arun Kumar|date=April 2004|title=Agrarian Conflict, Internal Displacement, and Trafficking of Mexican Women: The Case of Chiapas State|url=http://paa2004.princeton.edu/papers/40481|journal=Population Association of America|volume=|pages=|via=PAA}}</ref> Similarly to the Central American civil wars, the sexual violence that accompanied this conflict drove many shunned women to turn to sex work and helped jump start the sex trade in those regions of Mexico.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n==Anti-trafficking laws and policies==\nMexico ratified the [[United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime|United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime]] (or Palermo Convention) on April 11, 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://treaties.un.org/Pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=IND&mtdsg_no=XVIII-12&chapter=18&clang=_en|title=United Nations Treaty Collection|website=treaties.un.org|language=EN|access-date=2019-03-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306044115/https://treaties.un.org/Pages/ViewDetails.aspx?src=IND&mtdsg_no=XVIII-12&chapter=18&clang=_en|archive-date=2019-03-06|url-status=live}}</ref> The Convention includes a [[Protocol against the Smuggling of Migrants by Land, Sea and Air|\"Protocol Against the Smuggling of Migrants by Land, Sea, and Air]]\" and a \"[[Protocol to Prevent, Suppress and Punish Trafficking in Persons, especially Women and Children|Protocol to Suppress, Prevent, and Punish Trafficking in Persons, Especially Women and Children]]\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cicero-Dominguez|first=Salvador A.|date=Winter 2005|title=Assessing the U.S.-Mexico Fight Against Trafficking and Smuggling: Unintended Results of U.S. Immigration Policy|url=http://scholarlycommons.law.northwestern.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1036&context=njihr|journal=Northwestern Journal of International Human Rights|volume=4|pages=|via=Scholarly Commons|access-date=2017-10-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171009093031/http://scholarlycommons.law.northwestern.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1036&context=njihr|archive-date=2017-10-09|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Congress of the Union|Congress of Mexico]] passed a law on human trafficking in 2007 after which the Federal District and all of the states passed anti-trafficking measures themselves.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Rietig|first=Victoria|date=November 2012|title=New Law, Old Impunity: Mexico has a new Anti-trafficking law, but will it Address the Country's Problems?|url=http://oxmofm.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/Rietig-FINAL.pdf|journal=Oxford Monitor of Forced Migration|volume=2|pages=|via=Oxford Monitor of Forced Migration|access-date=2017-10-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228013846/http://oxmofm.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/Rietig-FINAL.pdf|archive-date=2013-02-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> In an attempt to harmonize the varied penal codes on the subject of human trafficking, the government passed a new anti-trafficking law in 2012 that criminalized all participants in the act of trafficking (including consumers) and unified local laws.<ref name=\":3\" /> The law was further reformed in 2014.<ref name=\":4\" /> In an effort to address the demand for forced labor, the [[Secretariat of Labor and Social Welfare|Secretary of Labor and Social Welfare]] developed a series of workshops and trainings in 2010 to prevent child labor and trafficking for forced labor.<ref name=\"dos\" /> It included media materials that explain how labor recruiting agents can deceive individuals in order to recruit them for forced labor.<ref name=\"dos\" /> However, while Mexican officials recognize human trafficking as a serious problem, NGOs and government representatives report that some local officials tolerate and are sometimes complicit in trafficking, impeding implementation of anti-trafficking statutes.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\"dos\" /> Mexico has publicly endorsed the United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime\u2019s Blue Heart Campaign against Human Trafficking, becoming the first country in Latin America to do so.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/blueheart/en/about.html|title=About the Blue Heart|last=nancy.cao|website=www.unodc.org|access-date=2017-10-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803041919/http://www.unodc.org/blueheart/en/about.html|archive-date=2017-08-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Trafficking across the border with the United States==\n{{See also|Human trafficking in the United States|Human trafficking in Texas|Human trafficking in California|Human trafficking in Arizona|Coyotaje}}\n[[File:Border Region.png|thumb|330x330px|The U.S.-Mexico border with the area up to 100 miles from the border demarcated.]]\nA third of the people annually trafficked into the United States are from [[Latin America]], and the vast majority of these people enter the US through the [[Mexico-United States border]].<ref name=\":5\" /> This extremely porous border has historically been the site of one of the most protracted labor migrations in the world, and is North America's largest transit site for young children exploited in labor and sex trafficking as of 2011.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal | last1 = Butler | first1 = Cheryl | year = 2012 | title = Sex Slavery in the Lone Star State: Does the Texas Human Trafficking Legislation of 2011 Protect Minors? | url = | journal = Akron Law Review | volume = 45 | issue = | pages = 843\u201385 }}</ref> Texas is a particularly important transit site for domestic trafficking; around twenty percent of domestic trafficking victims pass through the state at some point on their journeys.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite journal | last1 = Ugarte | first1 = Marisa B.| last2 = Zarate | first2 = Laura | last3 = Farley | first3 = Melissa | author-link3 = Melissa Farley | title = Prostitution and trafficking of women and children from Mexico to the United States | journal = [[Journal of Aggression, Maltreatment & Trauma|Journal of Trauma Practice]] | volume = 2 | issue = 3/4 | pages = 147\u2013165 | doi = 10.1300/J189v02n03_08 | date = January 2004 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal | last1 = Garza | first1 = Rocio | year = 2011 | title = Addressing Human Trafficking Along the United States-Mexico Border: The Need for a Bilateral Partnership | url = | journal = Cardozo Journal of International and Comparative Law | volume = 19 | issue = 413| pages = 413\u201352 }}</ref>\n\n\"[[Coyotaje|Coyote]]\" is the colloquial term used to refer to migrant smugglers along the Mexico- United States border.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite journal | last1 = Hofmann | first1 = Susanne | year = 2015 | title = Borderline Slavery: Mexico, United States, and the Human Trade - Edited by Tiano, Susan and Murphy-Aguilar, Moira | url = | journal = Bulletin of Latin American Research | volume = 34 | issue = 2| pages = 279\u201381 | doi = 10.1111 }}</ref> In the past, the coyote-migrant relationship ended once the smuggler delivered the migrant to the U.S.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal | last1 = Chacon | first1 = Jennifer | year = 2006 | title = Misery and Mypoia: Understanding the Failures of U.S. Efforts to Stop Human Trafficking | url = | journal = Fordham Law Review | volume = 74 | issue = 6| pages = 2977\u20133040 }}</ref> However, it has become increasingly commonplace for coyotes to coerce migrants into exploitative labor arrangements upon reaching their destination in the U.S (frequently a different one from that which they paid to be smuggled to).<ref name=\":0\" /> These labor agreements frequently involve forced agricultural labor and/or sex work, conditions that migrants would never have consented to had they been previously aware of them.<ref name=\":0\" /> Coyotes use unpaid debt as a threat in order to force migrants into such arrangements. The rising costs of smuggling, a result of increased border security and enforcement, has made it far more common for migrants to become heavily indebted to smugglers.<ref name=\":0\" /> Additionally, the expansion of the coyote's role to include transporting migrants to a final destination within the U.S., rather than simply transporting them across the border, incurs additional expenses that the migrant must pay, and so increases the likelihood of their being exploited and trafficked by the coyotes as forced laborers or sex workers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSmugglers sometimes pretend to offer reduced fees to women and child migrants and then sexually assault or rape them as a form of substitute \"payment\".<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Estes|first=Richard J.|last2=Weiner|first2=Niel Alan|date=February 20, 2002|title=The Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children in the U.S., Canada, and Mexico|url=http://www.gems-girls.org/Estes%20Wiener%202001.pdf|journal=School of Social Work|volume=|pages=|via=|access-date=November 12, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229014824/http://www.gems-girls.org/Estes%20Wiener%202001.pdf|archive-date=December 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Human traffickers masquerading as coyotes often use false promises of guaranteed jobs to lure migrants, and will sometimes kidnap women and children along the journey, either for ransom from their families, or to be sold in the US into servitude or prostitution.<ref name=\":5\" /> Many unaccompanied children also make the crossing from Mexico to the U.S.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.unicefusa.org/mission/emergencies/child-refugees/central-america-child-migrants|title=Central America Child Migrants|work=UNICEF USA|access-date=2017-09-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922052810/https://www.unicefusa.org/mission/emergencies/child-refugees/central-america-child-migrants|archive-date=2017-09-22|url-status=live}}</ref> Unaccompanied minors are sometimes sold into prostitution by the trafficker, and their families are falsely led to believe that they died during transit.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nWithin the United States, the [[Victims of Trafficking and Violence Protection Act of 2000]] serves as a legal framework within which many perpetrators of trafficking are tried, but victims of trafficking are generally punished on equal footing with perpetrators if intercepted during the process of entering the country.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite journal|last=Kappelhoff|first=Michael J.|date=Fall 2008|title=Federal Prosecution of Human Trafficking Cases: Striking a Blow Against Modern Day Slavery|url=https://ir.stthomas.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=https://www.google.com/&httpsredir=1&article=1173&context=ustlj|journal=University of St. Thomas Law Journal|volume=6|pages=9\u201320|via=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Human rights in Mexico]]\n* [[International child abduction in Mexico]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Americas topic|Human trafficking in}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Human Trafficking In Mexico}}\n[[Category:Human trafficking in Mexico| ]]\n[[Category:Human trafficking by country|Mexico]]\n[[Category:Human trafficking in North America|Mexico]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTrafficking across the border with the United States:Fixed doi error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_trafficking_in_Mexico"}
